{"case_id": "case-009-d4-25", "container": "HC2", "pipeline_depth": 4, "message": "HFrEF EF 30%, on lisinopril and carvedilol. eGFR 48. Can we add empagliflozin?", "latency_ms": 11869, "llm_calls": 2, "tokens_in": 218, "tokens_out": 300, "cost_usd": 0.0002127, "task_success": true, "abstained": false, "answer": "**Recommendation:**\n\nEmpagliflozin is appropriate for this patient. SGLT2 inhibitors, including empagliflozin, are guideline-directed medical therapy for HFrEF, demonstrating significant reductions in cardiovascular death and heart failure hospitalizations regardless of diabetes status. Clinical trials (e.g., EMPEROR-Reduced) and current guidelines support the initiation of empagliflozin in patients with HFrEF down to an eGFR of 20-25 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2. The patient's eGFR of 48 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 is well above this threshold.\n\n**Citations:**\n\n1.  Anker SD, et al. Empagliflozin in Patients with Heart Failure and Reduced Ejection Fraction. *N Engl J Med*. 2020;383(15):1413-1424.\n2.  McDonagh TA, et al. 2021 ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of acute and chronic heart failure. *Eur Heart J*. 2021;42(36):3599-3726.\n3.  Heiden", "tool_calls": 0, "hop_metrics": [{"hop": "vector_ingress", "latency_ms": 2, "llm_calls": 0, "tokens_in": 0, "tokens_out": 0, "tool_calls": 0}, {"hop": "cache_gate", "latency_ms": 0, "llm_calls": 0, "tokens_in": 0, "tokens_out": 0, "tool_calls": 0}, {"hop": "analyze", "latency_ms": 5765, "llm_calls": 1, "tokens_in": 95, "tokens_out": 41, "tool_calls": 0}, {"hop": "writer", "latency_ms": 6098, "llm_calls": 1, "tokens_in": 123, "tokens_out": 259, "tool_calls": 0}], "embed_count": 2, "cache_hit": true, "cache_score": 1.0, "variant": "exact_repeat", "error": null}
